      <constitutionalAuthorityStatementText>&lt;pre&gt;[Congressional Record Volume 170, Number 153 (Friday, October 4, 2024)][House]From the Congressional Record Online through the Government Publishing Office [&lt;a href="https://www.gpo.gov"&gt;www.gpo.gov&lt;/a&gt;]By Mr. ISSA:H.R. 9922.Congress has the power to enact this legislation pursuantto the following:Article I, Section 8, clause 18 allows Congress to make alllaws ``which shall be necessary and proper for carrying intoexecution'' any ``other'' powers vested by the Constitutionin the Government of the United States.According to the Supreme Court, the Necessary and ProperClause gives Congress the ``power to make laws for carryinginto execution all the judgments which the judicialdepartment has power to pronounce'' (Wayman v. Southard, 10Wheat. 1, 22 (1825)), and, thereby, Congress has ``undoubtedpower to regulate the practice and procedure of federalcourts.'' See Sibbach v. Wilson &amp; Co., 312 U.S. 1, 9 (1941).The single subject of this legislation is:To amend title 28, United States Code, to provide fortransparency and oversight of third-party beneficiaries incivil actions.[Page H5854]&lt;/pre&gt;</constitutionalAuthorityStatementText>
